<taxonomicName LSID="9CF64C2F-3D8D-5761-B29E-7FB9777AAF51" authority="Johnston, 1840" authorityName="Johnston" authorityYear="1840" class="Polychaeta" family="Capitellidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" order="Capitellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Travisia Johnston, 1840</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
These distinctive, grub-like polychaetes with rugose epidermis were first described by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222934009512507" author="Johnston, G" journalOrPublisher="Annals and Magazine for Natural History London" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="368 - 375" refId="B50" refString="Johnston, G, 1840. Miscellanea Zoologica. British Annelids. Annals and Magazine for Natural History London 1: 368 - 375" title="Miscellanea Zoologica. British Annelids." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222934009512507" volume="1" year="1840">Johnston (1840)</bibRefCitation>
with the discovery of 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia forbesii" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="forbesii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia forbesii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Johnston, 1840. Later, Kinberg (1866) established the genus 
<taxonomicName genus="Dindymenes" lsidName="Dindymenes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Dindymenes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin, R" journalOrPublisher="Memories of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 514" refId="B16" refString="Chamberlin, R, 1919. The AnnelidaPolychaeta. Memories of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College 48: 1 - 514" title="The AnnelidaPolychaeta." volume="48" year="1919">Chamberlin (1919)</bibRefCitation>
established the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1919" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1919" class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Kesun" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Kesun" order="Polychaeta incertae sedis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Kesun</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which he differentiated from 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the complete absence of branchiae. Following a cladistic analysis of morphological characters, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dauvin, J-C" journalOrPublisher="Memoires du Museum national d'histoire naturelle" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="169 - 184" refId="B19" refString="Dauvin, J-C, Bellan, G, 1994. Systematics, ecology and biogeographical relationships in the sub-family Travisiinae (Polychaeta, Opheliidae). Memoires du Museum national d'histoire naturelle 162: 169 - 184" title="Systematics, ecology and biogeographical relationships in the sub-family Travisiinae (Polychaeta, Opheliidae)." volume="162" year="1994">Dauvin and Bellan (1994)</bibRefCitation>
synonymized 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1919" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1919" class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Kesun" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Kesun" order="Polychaeta incertae sedis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Kesun</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1919" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1919" class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Dindymenides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dindymenides" order="Polychaeta incertae sedis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Dindymenides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and recognized at least 27 species. Important species-level characters include the presence of lobes, the position and relative size of the nephridiopores, and the total number of chaetigers, which appears to be stable in most, but not all, species (
<bibRefCitation author="Dauvin, J-C" journalOrPublisher="Memoires du Museum national d'histoire naturelle" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="169 - 184" refId="B19" refString="Dauvin, J-C, Bellan, G, 1994. Systematics, ecology and biogeographical relationships in the sub-family Travisiinae (Polychaeta, Opheliidae). Memoires du Museum national d'histoire naturelle 162: 169 - 184" title="Systematics, ecology and biogeographical relationships in the sub-family Travisiinae (Polychaeta, Opheliidae)." volume="162" year="1994">Dauvin and Bellan 1994</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The higher taxonomic position of 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been in dispute for some time. While usually placed in 
<taxonomicName family="Opheliidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Opheliidae</taxonomicName>
, its relationship with 
<taxonomicName authority="Malmgren, 1867" authorityName="Malmgren" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Capitellidae" genus="Scalibregmatidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scalibregmatidae" order="Capitellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scalibregmatidae</taxonomicName>
has also been long suggested (
<bibRefCitation author="Ashworth, JH" journalOrPublisher="Quarterly Journal of Microscopical Science, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="237 - 309" refId="B2" refString="Ashworth, JH, 1902. The anatomy of Scalibregmainflatum Rathke. Quarterly Journal of Microscopical Science, London 45: 237 - 309" title="The anatomy of Scalibregmainflatum Rathke." volume="45" year="1902">Ashworth 1902</bibRefCitation>
), mainly due to possession of rugose epidermis. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1086/407180" author="Hartmann-Schroeder, G" journalOrPublisher="Die Tierwelt Deutschlands und der angrenzenden Meeresteile nach ihren Merkmalen und nach ihrer Lebensweise" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 594" refId="B45" refString="Hartmann-Schroeder, G, 1971. Annelida, borstenwurmer, polychaeta. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands und der angrenzenden Meeresteile nach ihren Merkmalen und nach ihrer Lebensweise 58: 1 - 594" title="Annelida, borstenwurmer, polychaeta." url="https://doi.org/10.1086/407180" volume="58" year="1971">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hartmann-SchrÃ¶der">Hartmann-Schroeder</normalizedToken>
(1971)
</bibRefCitation>
created a subfamily, 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Travisiinae">Travisiinae</taxonomicName>
, in 
<taxonomicName family="Opheliidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Opheliidae</taxonomicName>
to accommodate 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. More recently, phylogenetic analyses were employed to answer this question. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.998.1.1" author="Persson, J" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 14" refId="B77" refString="Persson, J, Pleijel, F, 2005. On the phylogenetic relationships of Axiokebuita, Travisia and Scalibregmatidae (Polychaeta). Zootaxa 998: 1 - 14" title="On the phylogenetic relationships of Axiokebuita, Travisia and Scalibregmatidae (Polychaeta)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.998.1.1" volume="998" year="2005">Persson and Pleijel (2005)</bibRefCitation>
used molecular data to recover 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nested within the 
<taxonomicName authority="Malmgren, 1867" authorityName="Malmgren" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Capitellidae" genus="Scalibregmatidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scalibregmatidae" order="Capitellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scalibregmatidae</taxonomicName>
, and molecular analysis of 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/14772000.2010.517810" author="Paul, C" journalOrPublisher="Systematics and Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="507 - 512" refId="B71" refString="Paul, C, Halanych, KM, Tiedemann, R, Bleidorn, C, 2010. Molecules reject an opheliid affinity for Travisia (Annelida). Systematics and Biodiversity 8: 507 - 512" title="Molecules reject an opheliid affinity for Travisia (Annelida)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/14772000.2010.517810" volume="8" year="2010">Paul et al. (2010)</bibRefCitation>
rejected affinity with 
<taxonomicName family="Opheliidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Opheliidae</taxonomicName>
and found strong support sister-group relationship of 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Malmgren, 1867" authorityName="Malmgren" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Capitellidae" genus="Scalibregmatidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scalibregmatidae" order="Capitellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scalibregmatidae</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/jmor.20237" author="Law, CJ" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Morphology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="548 - 571" refId="B56" refString="Law, CJ, Dorgan, KM, Rouse, GW, 2014. Relating divergence in polychaete musculature to different burrowing behaviors: A study using Opheliidae (Annelida). Journal of Morphology 42: 548 - 571" title="Relating divergence in polychaete musculature to different burrowing behaviors: A study using Opheliidae (Annelida)." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/jmor.20237" volume="42" year="2014">Law et al. (2014)</bibRefCitation>
again placed 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within 
<taxonomicName authority="Malmgren, 1867" authorityName="Malmgren" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Capitellidae" genus="Scalibregmatidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scalibregmatidae" order="Capitellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scalibregmatidae</taxonomicName>
using molecular data. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Blake, JA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B13" refString="Blake, JA, Maciolek, NJ, 2016. Travisiidae Hartmann-Schroeder, 1971, new family status. In: Purschke G, Boeggemann M, Westheide W (Eds) Handbook of Zoology. De Gruyter, Berlin." title="Travisiidae Hartmann-Schroeder, 1971, new family status. In: Purschke G, Boeggemann M, Westheide W (Eds) Handbook of Zoology. De Gruyter, Berlin." year="2016">Blake and Maciolek (2016)</bibRefCitation>
proposed a new family, 
<taxonomicName family="Travisiidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Travisiidae</taxonomicName>
, to accommodate 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Travisiidae" genus="Travisia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Travisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Travisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have predominantly deep-water distribution (
<bibRefCitation author="Blake, JA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B13" refString="Blake, JA, Maciolek, NJ, 2016. Travisiidae Hartmann-Schroeder, 1971, new family status. In: Purschke G, Boeggemann M, Westheide W (Eds) Handbook of Zoology. De Gruyter, Berlin." title="Travisiidae Hartmann-Schroeder, 1971, new family status. In: Purschke G, Boeggemann M, Westheide W (Eds) Handbook of Zoology. De Gruyter, Berlin." year="2016">Blake and Maciolek 2016</bibRefCitation>
) and two species, one of them very abundant, were found in UKSR material.
</paragraph>
